<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" box="[199,1325,596,622]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,596,622]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named in reference to the fictional character Hunchback of Notre-Dame.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,429,632,658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Generic placement.</emphasis>
. This species was placed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. Koch" authorityYear="1872" box="[737,859,632,658]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[737,859,632,658]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Carepalxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the females have two large cephalic humps. The male does not match the descriptions of the Australian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. Koch" authorityYear="1872" box="[850,972,668,694]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[850,972,668,694]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Carepalxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males by the presence of the following characters: the unbranched second tibia (
<figureCitation box="[622,707,704,730]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,717,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-258@4.[163,1425,705,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–15. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 11, Male left palp. 12–15, Male habitus (12, dorsal; 13, ventral; 14, frontal; 15, lateral). Voucher: 1–3, 6–8, (DZUB 9000); 4, 5, 9, 10, (DZUB 9274); 11–15, (DZUB 9284). Scale bars: genitalia, 0.25 mm; other drawings, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824329/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
), third and fourth coxae armed with macrosetae (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1365,704,730]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,717,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-258@4.[163,1425,705,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–15. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 11, Male left palp. 12–15, Male habitus (12, dorsal; 13, ventral; 14, frontal; 15, lateral). Voucher: 1–3, 6–8, (DZUB 9000); 4, 5, 9, 10, (DZUB 9274); 11–15, (DZUB 9284). Scale bars: genitalia, 0.25 mm; other drawings, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824329/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), rodshaped paramedian apophysis connected to the conductor. This issue is discussed on the diagnostic notes section below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,812,838]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" box="[667,870,812,838]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus">
<emphasis box="[667,791,812,838]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. camelus</emphasis>
Simon
</taxonomicName>
due to the shape of the epigynum. Both share wide lateral plates and a hidden median plate in posterior view, moreover the scape is long and has a longitudinal groove. 
<taxonomicName authority="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta, 2022" authorityName="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,404,884,910]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quasimodo" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[151,404,884,910]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Carepalxis quasimodo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[413,477,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[413,477,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is different by having a larger scape and a narrower base. In ventral view, the scape has almost half the width of the base rather than one quarter (
<figureCitation box="[827,896,920,946]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[211,1372,217,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 1–5, Epigynum (1, posterior; 1 ventral; 3, lateral; 4, ventral without scape; 5, posterior, cleared). 6–10, Female habitus; 6–8, female from Brasília (6, dorsal; 7, lateral; 8, frontal); 9–10, female from Jaborandi (9, dorsal; 10 lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824326/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). The scape is slightly curved instead of straight. Additionally, the females lack the anterior median abdominal protuberance present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" box="[1120,1245,956,982]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus">
<emphasis box="[1120,1245,956,982]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. camelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Levi, H. W." box="[1260,1387,956,982]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" pagination="251 - 264" refId="ref6928" refString="Levi, H. W. (1992) The American species of the orb-weaver genus Carepalxis and the new genus Rubrepeira (Araneae: Araneidae). Psyche: A Journal of Entomology, 98 (2 - 3), 251 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 1991 / 26493" type="journal article" year="1992">Levi, 1992</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 4). It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Petrunkevitch" authorityName="Petrunkevitch" box="[363,652,992,1018]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perpera">
<emphasis box="[363,487,992,1018]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. perpera</emphasis>
Petrunkevitch
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta, 2022" authorityName="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta" authorityYear="2022" box="[711,828,992,1018]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="topazio" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[711,828,992,1018]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. topazio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[838,903,992,1018]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[838,903,992,1018]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by having only one pair of tubercles (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[211,1372,217,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 1–5, Epigynum (1, posterior; 1 ventral; 3, lateral; 4, ventral without scape; 5, posterior, cleared). 6–10, Female habitus; 6–8, female from Brasília (6, dorsal; 7, lateral; 8, frontal); 9–10, female from Jaborandi (9, dorsal; 10 lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824326/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Figs. 6, 7, 9, 10</figureCitation>
. The posterior median plate is hidden, unlike those of similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta, 2022" authorityName="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta" authorityYear="2022" box="[948,1064,1028,1054]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="topazio" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[948,1064,1028,1054]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. topazio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1073,1137,1028,1054]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1073,1137,1028,1054]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1154,1239,1028,1054]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–21" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[178,1417,449,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-78@5.[151,1435,417,1839]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 16–21. Carepalxis topazio n. sp. 16–18, Epigynum (16, ventral; 17, lateral; 18, posterior). 19–21, Female habitus (19, dorsal; 20, frontal; 21, lateral). Voucher: 16–21, (DZUB 8699). Scale bars: genitalia, 0.25 mm; other drawings, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824332/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). The male is the first of this genus found in the Americas. It differs from the Australian 
<taxonomicName authority="Keyserling" authorityName="Keyserling" box="[957,1218,1064,1090]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcifera">
<emphasis box="[957,1087,1064,1090]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. furcifera</emphasis>
Keyserling
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Keyserling" authorityName="Keyserling" authorityYear="1886" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis box="[1275,1436,1064,1090]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. tuberculata</emphasis>
